# Debugging Node.js Applications

Node.js has first-class debugging support through the V8 inspector protocol. You can set breakpoints, step through code, inspect variables, profile performance, and hunt memory leaks — all without third-party tools.

## Starting the Inspector

The `--inspect` flag starts the V8 inspector agent:

```bash
# Start inspector (doesn't pause execution)
node --inspect app.js
# Debugger listening on ws://127.0.0.1:9229/uuid

# Start inspector and pause on first line
node --inspect-brk app.js

# Custom host and port
node --inspect=0.0.0.0:9230 app.js

# Inspect a running process (send SIGUSR1)
kill -USR1 <pid>
```

Once the inspector is running, connect with:
- **Chrome DevTools**: Open `chrome://inspect` in Chrome, click "inspect" on the listed target
- **VS Code**: Use the built-in debugger (see launch.json below)
- **Node.js built-in**: `node inspect app.js` (CLI debugger)

## VS Code Debugging

Create `.vscode/launch.json`:

```json
{
  "version": "0.2.0",
  "configurations": [
    {
      "type": "node",
      "request": "launch",
      "name": "Launch Program",
      "program": "${workspaceFolder}/src/index.js",
      "console": "integratedTerminal",
      "skipFiles": ["<node_internals>/**"]
    },
    {
      "type": "node",
      "request": "attach",
      "name": "Attach to Process",
      "port": 9229,
      "skipFiles": ["<node_internals>/**"]
    },
    {
      "type": "node",
      "request": "launch",
      "name": "Debug Tests",
      "program": "${workspaceFolder}/node_modules/.bin/jest",
      "args": ["--runInBand"],
      "console": "integratedTerminal"
    }
  ]
}
```

## Console Methods

Beyond `console.log`, Node.js provides powerful console methods:

```javascript
// Table formatting for arrays and objects
console.table([{ name: 'Alice', age: 30 }, { name: 'Bob', age: 25 }]);

// Timing operations
console.time('db-query');
await db.query('SELECT * FROM users');
console.timeEnd('db-query');  // db-query: 45.123ms

// Count invocations
function processItem(item) {
  console.count('processItem');  // processItem: 1, processItem: 2, ...
}

// Stack traces
console.trace('Reached this point');

// Grouped output
console.group('User processing');
console.log('Fetching user...');
console.log('Validating...');
console.groupEnd();

// Deep object inspection
console.dir(complexObject, { depth: null, colors: true });

// Conditional logging
console.assert(value > 0, 'Value must be positive:', value);
```

## NODE_DEBUG Environment Variable

Enable debug output from Node.js core modules:

```bash
# Debug filesystem operations
NODE_DEBUG=fs node app.js

# Debug multiple modules
NODE_DEBUG=fs,net,tls node app.js

# Debug HTTP module
NODE_DEBUG=http node app.js

# Available modules: fs, net, tls, http, http2, stream, module, timer
```

## Diagnostic Reports

Node.js can generate JSON diagnostic reports on crashes or on demand:

```bash
# Generate report on fatal error
node --report-on-fatalerror app.js

# Generate report on uncaught exception
node --report-uncaught-exception app.js

# Generate report on signal (SIGUSR2 by default)
node --report-on-signal app.js

# Custom report directory
node --report-directory=/var/reports app.js
```

```javascript
// Generate report programmatically
process.report.writeReport();
process.report.writeReport('/path/to/report.json');

// Get report as JSON object
const report = process.report.getReport();
console.log(report.header.nodeVersion);
console.log(report.javascriptHeap);
```

Reports include: Node.js version, platform info, JavaScript heap stats, native stack trace, libuv handle info, environment variables, and loaded modules.

## Heap Snapshots and Memory Leaks

```javascript
const v8 = require('node:v8');
const fs = require('node:fs');

// Write heap snapshot to file
const filename = v8.writeHeapSnapshot();
console.log(`Heap snapshot written to ${filename}`);

// Or via inspector
const inspector = require('node:inspector');
const session = new inspector.Session();
session.connect();
session.post('HeapProfiler.takeHeapSnapshot', null, (err, r) => {
  // Snapshot taken
});
```

Common memory leak patterns:
- **Event listeners not removed**: Use `emitter.removeListener()` or `AbortController`
- **Closures capturing large objects**: Break references when done
- **Global caches without eviction**: Use `Map` with size limits or `WeakMap`/`WeakRef`
- **Unresolved promises**: Always handle rejections

```bash
# Track heap growth over time
node --max-old-space-size=512 app.js

# Expose GC for testing
node --expose-gc app.js
# Then in code: global.gc();
```

## CPU Profiling

```bash
# V8 CPU profile (generates .cpuprofile file)
node --cpu-prof app.js
node --cpu-prof --cpu-prof-dir=./profiles app.js

# V8 tick profiler (low-level)
node --prof app.js
# Process the log
node --prof-process isolate-0xNNNN-v8.log > profile.txt
```

Open `.cpuprofile` files in Chrome DevTools (Performance tab) or VS Code to see flame charts.

## Async Stack Traces

Node.js supports async stack traces that show the full call chain across async boundaries:

```bash
# Enabled by default since Node 16
# Provides clear traces across await, setTimeout, Promise.then
node app.js
```

```javascript
// Example: clear async trace
async function fetchUser(id) {
  const response = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);
  return response.json();  // Error here shows full async chain
}

async function handleRequest(req) {
  const user = await fetchUser(req.params.id);
  return user;
}
```

## Debugging Common Issues

### Unhandled Promise Rejections
```javascript
// Catch all unhandled rejections
process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason, promise) => {
  console.error('Unhandled rejection at:', promise, 'reason:', reason);
  // In production: log and exit
  process.exit(1);
});
```

### Event Loop Blocking
```javascript
// Detect blocked event loop
const start = process.hrtime.bigint();
setInterval(() => {
  const delta = Number(process.hrtime.bigint() - start) / 1e6;
  const drift = delta % 1000;
  if (drift > 50) console.warn(`Event loop blocked for ${drift}ms`);
}, 1000);
```

### Debugging with util.debuglog
```javascript
const util = require('node:util');
const debug = util.debuglog('myapp');

// Only prints when NODE_DEBUG=myapp
debug('Processing request %s', requestId);
```

## Third-Party Tools

| Tool | Purpose | Install |
|------|---------|--------|
| **clinic.js** | Performance analysis suite (Doctor, Bubbleprof, Flame) | `npm i -g clinic` |
| **0x** | Flame graph generation | `npm i -g 0x` |
| **ndb** | Chrome DevTools-based debugger | `npm i -g ndb` |
| **why-is-node-running** | Track active handles preventing exit | `npm i why-is-node-running` |
| **trace-unhandled** | Better unhandled rejection traces | `npm i trace-unhandled` |

```bash
# Flame graph with 0x
0x app.js

# Clinic.js analysis
clinic doctor -- node app.js
clinic flame -- node app.js
clinic bubbleprof -- node app.js
```

## Environment Variables

| Variable | Purpose |
|----------|----------|
| `NODE_DEBUG` | Enable debug output for core modules |
| `NODE_OPTIONS` | Default CLI flags (e.g., `--inspect`) |
| `NODE_V8_COVERAGE` | Directory for V8 coverage output |
| `UV_THREADPOOL_SIZE` | libuv thread pool size for async I/O |
